MARSEILLE, France (AP) — La Rochelle stunned Leinster with a last-minute try to win its first European Champions Cup 24-21 in the final on Saturday at Stade Velodrome.A massive underdog going into the final, La Rochelle went ahead with a mere 17 seconds left on the clock when replacement scrumhalf Arthur Retiere squirmed his way over from a ruck on the Leinster line. Ihaia West added his third conversion and the French side made up for their defeat in the final a year ago.Six penalties by Leinster captain Jonathan Sexton and another penalty by his replacement Ross Byrne had them ahead 21-17 with 15 minutes to go and La Rochelle lock Thomas Lavault in the sin-bin.But La Rochelle laid siege to Leinster’s line, and was bolstered by the return of Lavault with five to go.Leinster, chasing a record-equalling fifth title, looked like holding on but Retiere found the smallest gap in the Irish team’s defense.ADVERTISEMENTIn the end, La Rochelle’s defense was also critical. The French side scored three tries and stopped Leinster scoring a try for the first time this season.Leinster picked the same side which thrashed defending champion Toulouse in the semifinals two weeks ago. However, La Rochelle coach Ronan O’Gara was without two influential former All Blacks in back-rower Victor Vito and scrumhalf Tawera Kerr-Barlow.RugbySuper Rugby quarterfinalists set after tight final roundSouth Africa 7s rebound in London after Toulouse failureMoana Pasifika upsets Brumbies, Western Force stay in raceCrusaders beat Reds 28-15 in Super Rugby, seal 2nd placeO’Gara, the Ireland flyhalf great, said, “We knew that Leinster are usually out of sight in the first half, so when we came in five down at halftime (12-7) we knew that was OK.“We had to take their time and space away and we knew we had to score tries to win. There was great heart. We could have rolled over, but we didn’t, and I think this is the start of something special.___More AP rugby: https://apnews.com/hub/rugby and https://twitter.com/AP_Sports